Step 1 — Add GitHub Secrets
Go to: GitHub repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret

Add all 5 secrets listed above. To get their values:

VERCEL_TOKEN: Vercel Dashboard → Account Settings → Tokens → Create
VERCEL_ORG_ID: Run vercel whoami --json or find in Vercel → Settings → General → "Your ID" (Team/Personal)
VERCEL_PROJECT_ID_TRT/POWERSTARTER/POWERFRAME: Each Vercel project → Settings → General → "Project ID"
Step 2 — Add Firebase Keys to Vercel (for each of the 3 projects)
In each Vercel project → Settings → Environment Variables, add:

Key	Scope
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY	All (Production, Preview, Development)
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN	All
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID	All
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET	All
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID	All
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID	All
FIREBASE_ADMIN_SA_JSON	Production + Preview only (server-side, never client)
The workflow uses vercel pull to sync Vercel env vars into the build — so you only need to set 
them in Vercel, not duplicate them in GitHub secrets.

Step 3 — Re-run the Vercel Deploy workflow
After adding all secrets, either:

Push a new commit to the copilot/init-monorepo-foundation-nextjs branch, or
Go to Actions → Vercel Deploy → Re-run all jobs
This will trigger a fresh run that will pass through CI → lint → typecheck → deploy all 3 apps.

TL;DR: The code is 100% ready. The action_required failure means the GitHub Secrets
(VERCEL_TOKEN, VERCEL_ORG_ID, the 3 project IDs) haven't been added yet, and the Firebase keys 
need to be entered in Vercel's dashboard. Once both are done, 
re-run the workflow and everything will deploy cleanly.




